==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|la}} {{term|academia|lang=la}}; see {{term|academy|lang=en}}. ''Academe'' (frequently capitalized) is a poetic name for the garden or grove near ancient Athens where {{w|Plato}} taught, supposedly named for its former owner, the hero Ἀκάδημος (''{{w|Akademos}};'' Ἑκάδημος, ''Hekademos'').

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈækədiːm/}}
*: {{rhymes|iːm}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{poetic}} An [[academy]]; a place of learning.
# {{poetic}} The [[scholarly]] life.

====Usage notes====
Poetic references are often to “the groves of Academe”, a translation of [[w:Horace|Horace’s]] ''inter silvas Academi''.<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=NHYXAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA169&dq=%22silvas+Academi%22&lr=&as_brr=1#PRA3-PA169,M1]</ref><ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=nVE3QD1Y5RAC&pg=PA14&dq=%22silvas+Academi%22&lr=&sig=pymz2Xcnaldixpke_6QPFsNSGxk]</ref>

